{
  "Which is an example of a chemical change?": "",
  "Breaking glass": "",
  "Cutting paper": "",
  "Melting ice": "",
  "Burning wood": "",
  "Burning wood is a chemical change — combustion produces new substances (carbon dioxide, water vapor, and ash). Cutting, breaking, and melting only change form or size without creating new substances.": "",
  "Which is a sign that a chemical change has occurred?": "",
  "Production of gas bubbles during a reaction": "",
  "Change in size": "",
  "Change in state (solid to liquid)": "",
  "Change in shape": "",
  "Gas production (bubbles) during a reaction indicates new gaseous substances are being formed — a sign of chemical change. Changes in size, state, and shape are physical changes that don't produce new substances.": "",
  "Dissolving sugar in water is a:": "",
  "Physical change": "",
  "Chemical change": "",
  "No change at all": "",
  "Nuclear change": "",
  "Dissolving is a physical change — sugar molecules disperse among water molecules but remain intact as sugar (C₁₂H₂₂O₁₁). You can recover the sugar by evaporating the water, proving no new substance was formed.": "",
  "Which is an example of a physical change?": "",
  "Cooking an egg": "",
  "Freezing water into ice": "",
  "Rusting iron": "",
  "Burning gasoline": "",
  "Freezing water changes its state from liquid to solid but the substance remains H₂O. Rusting, burning, and cooking all produce new substances with different chemical compositions.": "",
  "A new substance with different properties is formed during a:": "",
  "Shape change": "",
  "Phase change": "",
  "The defining characteristic of a chemical change is the formation of one or more new substances with different chemical properties. Physical, phase, and shape changes alter appearance but not chemical identity.": "",
  "Which clue suggests a chemical change has taken place?": "",
  "Evaporation of water from a puddle": "",
  "A permanent color change accompanied by formation of a new substance": "",
  "Melting butter in a pan": "",
  "Tearing a sheet of paper in half": "",
  "A permanent color change (like iron turning orange-brown as rust) indicates a new substance has formed. Evaporation, tearing, and melting are physical changes — the substances remain the same chemically.": "",
  "Baking a cake is an example of a:": "",
  "Dissolving": "",
  "Baking causes chemical reactions — proteins denature, sugars caramelize, and baking soda releases CO₂ gas. The batter transforms into cake with completely different properties, and you cannot un-bake a cake.": "",
  "Which of the following is a physical change?": "",
  "Crushing a soda can": "",
  "Tarnishing silver": "",
  "Digesting food": "",
  "Lighting a match": "",
  "Crushing a soda can only changes its shape — the aluminum remains aluminum. Digestion breaks down food molecules chemically, lighting a match involves combustion, and tarnishing silver forms silver sulfide — all chemical changes.": "",
  "The Law of Conservation of Mass states that:": "",
  "Mass is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction": "",
  "Mass only applies to physical changes, not chemical ones": "",
  "Mass increases whenever a chemical change occurs": "",
  "Mass always decreases in a chemical reaction due to energy loss": "",
  "Discovered by Antoine Lavoisier, this law states that the total mass of reactants equals the total mass of products in a chemical reaction. Atoms are rearranged, not created or destroyed. If a burning log seems to lose mass, the 'missing' mass left as gases (CO₂, H₂O).": "",
  "Physical changes are generally _____, while chemical changes are generally _____.": "",
  "Invisible; visible": "",
  "Reversible; irreversible": "",
  "Irreversible; reversible": "",
  "Fast; slow": "",
  "Physical changes like melting, freezing, and dissolving can usually be reversed by changing conditions. Chemical changes (burning, rusting) produce new substances that generally cannot be converted back to the originals by simple physical means.": "",
  "What is a 'physical change'?": "",
  "A change that only occurs at high temperatures": "",
  "A change in form, appearance, or state that does not alter the substance's chemical composition or identity": "",
  "A change that creates a completely new substance": "",
  "A change that always involves mixing two substances": "",
  "Physical changes alter how matter looks or what phase it's in, but the molecules remain the same. Ice, liquid water, and steam are all H₂O — only the arrangement and energy of molecules differ. The substance can usually be recovered.": "",
  "What is a 'chemical change'?": "",
  "The separation of a mixture into its components": "",
  "The movement of particles from hot to cold regions": "",
  "A process in which one or more new substances with different properties are formed through the rearrangement of atoms": "",
  "A change in shape or size of a substance": "",
  "In a chemical change (also called a chemical reaction), bonds between atoms break and reform in new arrangements, producing substances with different chemical formulas and properties. The original substances cannot be recovered by physical means.": "",
  "What is a 'precipitate'?": "",
  "A dissolved substance that changes color": "",
  "A gas that escapes from a boiling liquid": "",
  "An insoluble solid that forms when two solutions are mixed, indicating a chemical reaction has occurred": "",
  "The residue left after evaporating a solution": "",
  "When two clear solutions are mixed and a solid suddenly appears (often cloudy or as particles settling out), that solid is a precipitate. For example, mixing silver nitrate and sodium chloride solutions produces a white precipitate of silver chloride (AgCl).": "",
  "What does the term 'combustion' mean?": "",
  "Any reaction that absorbs energy from the surroundings": "",
  "The slow process of water evaporating from a surface": "",
  "The physical process of melting a solid with heat": "",
  "A rapid chemical reaction between a substance and oxygen that produces heat and light (burning)": "",
  "Combustion is a chemical reaction: fuel + O₂ → CO₂ + H₂O + energy (heat and light). It requires fuel, oxygen, and an ignition source (the fire triangle). A burning candle, car engine, and campfire all involve combustion.": "",
  "What does 'oxidation' mean?": "",
  "The process of cooling a substance below its freezing point": "",
  "The dissolving of a substance in water": "",
  "The process of a solid becoming a gas": "",
  "A chemical reaction in which a substance combines with oxygen, often resulting in corrosion or rust": "",
  "Oxidation involves the loss of electrons, often through reaction with oxygen. Iron rusting (4Fe + 3O₂ → 2Fe₂O₃) and apple browning are everyday examples. In broader chemistry, oxidation is defined as electron loss, even without oxygen.": "",
  "What does 'decomposition' mean in chemistry?": "",
  "Two substances combining to form one compound": "",
  "A chemical reaction in which a single compound breaks down into two or more simpler substances": "",
  "A physical change where a solid breaks into smaller pieces": "",
  "The process of dissolving a compound in water": "",
  "Decomposition reactions break complex substances into simpler ones. Example: 2H₂O₂ → 2H₂O + O₂ (hydrogen peroxide decomposes into water and oxygen gas). This is the opposite of a synthesis reaction, where simpler substances combine.": "",
  "What does 'synthesis reaction' mean?": "",
  "A physical change where substances are mixed together": "",
  "A reaction where a compound splits into simpler parts": "",
  "The process of separating a mixture by distillation": "",
  "A chemical reaction in which two or more substances combine to form a single, more complex product": "",
  "Synthesis (combination) reactions follow the pattern A + B → AB. Example: 2Na + Cl₂ → 2NaCl (sodium and chlorine combine to form sodium chloride, table salt). The product has entirely different properties from the reactants.": "",
  "What does 'endothermic' mean in the context of a chemical change?": "",
  "A physical change that requires no energy": "",
  "A reaction that absorbs energy from its surroundings, causing the surroundings to feel cooler": "",
  "A reaction that releases energy, causing the surroundings to feel warmer": "",
  "A reaction that occurs only at very high temperatures": "",
  "Endothermic chemical changes absorb heat energy (endo = in, thermic = heat). A cold pack works by an endothermic reaction — dissolving ammonium nitrate absorbs heat from surroundings. The container feels cold because energy flows in.": "",
  "What does 'exothermic' mean in the context of a chemical change?": "",
  "A reaction that absorbs energy from the environment": "",
  "A reaction that releases energy to its surroundings, usually as heat or light": "",
  "A reaction that doesn't involve any energy change": "",
  "A reaction that only occurs in a vacuum": "",
  "Exothermic reactions release energy (exo = out). Combustion (burning), rusting, and hand warmers are exothermic — the surroundings feel warmer because energy flows out of the reacting system.": "",
  "What is meant by 'reversibility' when comparing physical and chemical changes?": "",
  "Reversibility only applies to changes involving gases": "",
  "Chemical changes are always reversible; physical changes are never reversible": "",
  "All changes in chemistry are reversible if enough energy is added": "",
  "Physical changes can usually be undone by reversing conditions; chemical changes typically cannot be easily reversed": "",
  "Melting ice can be reversed by refreezing (physical). Burning paper cannot be reversed — you can't turn ash and CO₂ back into paper (chemical). Some chemical reactions are reversible under specific conditions (like weak acid dissociation), but most everyday chemical changes are not.": "",
  "A student leaves a bicycle outside all winter. In spring, the handlebars are covered with a flaky, reddish-brown coating. She scrapes it off and notices the metal underneath is thinner. What type of change occurred and what evidence supports this?": "",
  "Chemical change — iron reacted with oxygen and moisture to form iron oxide (rust), a new substance with different properties and color": "",
  "Physical change — the coating can be scraped off, so nothing chemically changed": "",
  "No change — rust is just dirt that collected on the surface": "",
  "Physical change — the metal just changed color from exposure to cold": "",
  "Rusting is a classic chemical change: 4Fe + 3O₂ + water → 2Fe₂O₃·nH₂O. The red-brown color, flaky texture (different from smooth metal), and thinner underlying metal (iron was consumed) all confirm a new substance formed. Removing rust doesn't restore the original iron.": "",
  "A student cuts a banana and notices the exposed surface turns brown within 30 minutes. Her friend says, 'That's just a physical change — no big deal.' Is the friend correct?": "",
  "Yes — the color change is temporary and will reverse on its own": "",
  "Yes — the banana just dried out, which is a physical change": "",
  "No — browning is a chemical change called enzymatic oxidation, where enzymes react with oxygen to form melanin (a new brown substance)": "",
  "No — but it's a nuclear change, not a chemical one": "",
  "Enzymatic browning is a chemical change. When banana cells are damaged by cutting, the enzyme polyphenol oxidase reacts with oxygen to produce melanin — a new, brown-colored compound. Lemon juice (acid) can slow this by denaturing the enzyme, but it's still a chemical process.": "",
  "A camper mixes baking soda and vinegar in a bottle and quickly puts a balloon over the opening. The balloon inflates rapidly. What type of change occurred, and what evidence is there?": "",
  "Physical change — the gas was already trapped in the baking soda and was released": "",
  "No change — the balloon inflated due to heat from the vinegar": "",
  "Physical change — the baking soda just dissolved in the vinegar": "",
  "Chemical change — the gas (CO₂) inflating the balloon is a new substance produced by the reaction between NaHCO₃ and acetic acid": "",
  "NaHCO₃ + CH₃COOH → NaCH₃COO + H₂O + CO₂. The vigorous bubbling and gas production (inflating the balloon) are classic signs of a chemical change. New substances formed: sodium acetate, water, and carbon dioxide gas.": "",
  "A student weighs a sealed flask containing a mixture of solutions before and after mixing (causing a precipitate to form). The mass reads 150.0 g both times. She is confused — 'A new substance formed, so shouldn't mass change?' What explains this?": "",
  "The precipitate weighs the same because solids are denser than liquids": "",
  "The Law of Conservation of Mass — atoms are rearranged, not created or destroyed, so total mass stays the same in a sealed system": "",
  "No chemical change actually occurred — if mass didn't change, it must be physical": "",
  "The scale is broken — chemical changes always change mass": "",
  "The Law of Conservation of Mass (Lavoisier) states that mass is neither created nor destroyed in a chemical reaction. All the same atoms are present before and after — they've just been rearranged into new compounds. In a sealed system, the total mass remains constant.": "",
  "A child's glow stick works by bending the stick (breaking an inner glass vial) and mixing two chemicals. The stick glows green for several hours then fades. Is the glow a physical or chemical change?": "",
  "Chemical change — the two chemicals react to form new substances that release energy as light (chemiluminescence)": "",
  "No change — glow sticks use batteries to produce light": "",
  "Physical change — the chemicals just mixed together like salt and water": "",
  "Physical change — bending the stick is a physical action that created the glow": "",
  "Glow sticks produce light through chemiluminescence — a chemical reaction between hydrogen peroxide and a phenyl oxalate ester, catalyzed by a fluorescent dye. New substances form and energy is released as light (not heat). The reaction is irreversible, which is why glow sticks can't be 'recharged.'": "",
  "A construction worker mixes cement powder with water. Over the next few hours, the mixture becomes rock-hard and hot to the touch. Is this a physical or chemical change? What evidence supports your answer?": "",
  "Physical change — the water just evaporated, leaving the dry cement behind": "",
  "Chemical change — but the heat is just from sunlight, not the reaction": "",
  "Physical change — the cement just froze like water turning to ice": "",
  "Chemical change — cement undergoes a hydration reaction (combining with water) that forms new crystalline compounds and releases heat (exothermic)": "",
  "Cement hardening is a chemical change called hydration. Calcium silicate in cement reacts with water to form calcium silicate hydrate (C-S-H gel) — a completely new substance. Evidence: heat release (exothermic), irreversibility (you can't soften hardened concrete with water), and new properties (rock-hard vs. powder).": "",
  "During a cooking class, students observe these events: (1) boiling water, (2) caramelizing sugar, (3) chopping onions, (4) frying an egg. Which of these involve chemical changes?": "",
  "Only frying an egg — it's the only one that changes color": "",
  "All four — heat is involved in each, so they are all chemical": "",
  "None — cooking is always a physical change": "",
  "Caramelizing sugar and frying an egg — both produce new substances with different properties": "",
  "Boiling water (liquid → gas, same H₂O) and chopping onions (shape change) are physical changes. Caramelizing sugar breaks sucrose into new compounds (color change, new flavor — chemical). Frying an egg denatures proteins irreversibly, producing new substances (chemical).": "",
  "An antacid tablet is dropped into a glass of water and fizzes vigorously, then dissolves. A student argues this is a physical change because the tablet just dissolved. Another says it's chemical because of the fizzing. Who is right?": "",
  "Both are right — it's simultaneously physical and not a change at all": "",
  "The first student — all dissolving is a physical change": "",
  "Both are wrong — it's neither physical nor chemical": "",
  "The second student — the fizzing (CO₂ gas) is evidence of a chemical reaction between the base in the tablet and the citric acid": "",
  "Antacid tablets contain a base (NaHCO₃) and an acid (citric acid). When water allows them to mix, they react: NaHCO₃ + H₃C₆H₅O₇ → CO₂ + H₂O + sodium citrate. The gas production (fizzing) is a clear sign of chemical change. While dissolving alone is physical, the reaction is chemical.": "",
  "A forensic scientist examines a crime scene and finds a white powder. She adds a drop of acid and observes no reaction. She then heats the powder — it melts at 801°C without decomposing. She dissolves it in water and tests conductivity — it conducts electricity. What can she conclude?": "",
  "No identification is possible without knowing the color in accordance with classical theory": "",
  "The tests revealed physical properties (melting point, solubility, conductivity) and one chemical property (no reactivity with acid); the substance is likely table salt (NaCl)": "",
  "The substance is sugar because it dissolves in water, particularly regarding conductivity based on established principles": "",
  "All the tests were chemical changes, so the evidence is destroyed when evaluated systematically": "",
  "Melting point 801°C (physical property) matches NaCl. No reaction with acid (chemical property) rules out bases/carbonates. Dissolving and conducting electricity (physical properties) confirm an ionic compound. Together, these physical AND chemical property tests identify the substance without fully destroying it.": "",
  "A student burns a 10.0 g piece of steel wool in a sealed jar containing oxygen. After the reaction, the remaining solid (iron oxide) weighs 14.3 g. She says, 'This violates the Law of Conservation of Mass — the product weighs MORE than the steel wool!' Is she correct?": "",
  "Yes — the extra mass was created during the reaction, violating the law": "",
  "No — the scale is wrong because the jar is sealed": "",
  "No — the iron combined with oxygen from the jar (4.3 g of O₂), so the total mass of reactants (10.0 + 4.3 = 14.3 g) equals the product mass": "",
  "Yes — burning always creates mass from energy according to E = mc²": "",
  "The law is not violated. The iron (10.0 g) combined with oxygen gas (4.3 g) from inside the jar: 4Fe + 3O₂ → 2Fe₂O₃. The total mass of reactants (14.3 g) equals the product mass (14.3 g). She only weighed the solid — she forgot that oxygen gas also has mass and was consumed in the reaction.": ""
}